Karl Kraus (writer)

From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia


					Jump to:					navigation, 					search



Karl Kraus





Born
April 28, 1874 


Died
June 12, 1936  (aged 62)
Vienna 


Karl Kraus (April 28, 1874 – June 12, 1936) was an Austrian writer and journalist, known as a satirist, essayist, aphorist, playwright and poet. He directed his satire at the press, German culture, and German and Austrian politics. The Austrian author Stefan Zweig once called Kraus "the master of venomous ridicule" (der Meister des giftigen Spotts).[1] He was nominated for the Nobel Prize in Literature three times.[2]



